div></figure><p><span>I listen to podcasts. Often, though, I=E2=80=99ll lis=
ten to them to </span><em>supplement</em><span> or </span><em>reinforce</em=
><span> what I=E2=80=99m reading. So if I=E2=80=99m reading a book by, say,=
 Melissa Kearney, I=E2=80=99ll also listen to her interviews. This helps th=
e information to stick.</span></p><p>Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong=E2=80=94I l=
isten to comedy podcasts and fun stuff too. But I try to reserve that for t=
he end of the week or weekends.</p><div><hr></div><p>Reading takes time. Yo=
u have to make it a non-negotiable part of the day.</p><p>This precious tim=
e must be guarded! Some thinkers, as they rise in prominence as a result of=
 their interesting ideas, gradually devote less time to reading and more ti=
me to lucrative opportunities. This is a mistake. They are neglecting one o=
f the core habits that made them so interesting in the first place.</p><p>S=
imilar to a gym routine, it must be built right into your schedule and must=
 become an unthinking custom.</p><p><span>If you=E2=80=99re just starting o=
ut, focus on building habit first. In </span><em>Atomic Habits</em><span>, =
James Clear writes, =E2=80=9CIf you show up at the gym 5 days in a row=E2=
=80=94even for 2 minutes=E2=80=94you're casting votes for your new identity=
. You=E2=80=99re not worried about getting in shape. You=E2=80=99re focused=
 on becoming the type of person who doesn=E2=80=99t miss workouts.=E2=80=9D=
</span></p><p>The same goes for reading. In the beginning, don=E2=80=99t fo=
cus on volume. Don=E2=80=99t focus on trying to read a specific book in a s=
pecific amount of time. Focus instead on the concrete and the practical. Fo=
r example, each day you could schedule a time to sit down and read at least=
 ten pages. If that=E2=80=99s too much, try five. If that=E2=80=99s too muc=
h, then start with one page. Then go from there. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>In my c=
ase, I wake up in the morning and read as I drink coffee. This is how I sta=
rt the day. I tell myself I=E2=80=99ll read at least 25 pages (it used to b=
e 15 in grad school). Typically, though, once I get started, I=E2=80=99ll r=
ead more. </p><p>And as I mentioned, I keep books on my Kindle app. When I =
have a spare minute throughout the day, I read. &nbsp;</p><p>Don=E2=80=99t =
install games on your phone. If you can=E2=80=99t resist the pull of social=
 media, don=E2=80=99t put those apps on your phone. </p><p><span>Or experim=
ent with variants of </span><a href=3D"https://twitter.com/george__mack/sta=
tus/1681378342627311640" rel=3D"">George Mack=E2=80=99s</a><span> cocaine p=
hone and kale phone strategy, wherein he carries his =E2=80=9Ckale phone=E2=
=80=9D most of the time and only allows himself access to his =E2=80=9Ccoca=
ine phone=E2=80=9D at specific points in the day:</span></p><blockquote><p>=
<em>=E2=80=A2 Kale Phone - Full stack serotonin. Only notes, Kindle, Uber, =
Maps, and emergency number for 2-3 people to call.</em></p><p><em>=E2=80=A2=
 Cocaine Phone - Full stack dopamine. Twitter. Instagram. TikTok. WhatsApp.=
 Anyone can contact.</em></p></blockquote><p>Relatedly, do not sleep with y=
our phone anywhere in arm=E2=80=99s length of you.</p><p>Before bed, I char=
ge my phone on the other side of the room. And I=E2=80=99ll read (usually a=
 biography or memoir) until my eyes get tired and I go to sleep. Sometimes =
this period of reading gets me through 2 pages, sometimes 20 or more. </p><=
div><hr></div><p>What about money? </p><p>For me, books are similar to food=
. A necessity. Even when I was broke, I still bought books and still read a=
 lot. When I was a kid, before I started making my own money, I regularly v=
isited the school library and the local library. My teachers were sometimes=
 confounded by me because I never did homework and generally earned poor gr=
ades but would understand references they made to books they hadn=E2=80=99t=
 assigned to class.</p><p>Nowadays, if I see a book that interests me, I al=
ways just buy it. The upside of interesting and useful new information vast=
ly outweighs the downside of being out $20 or $30 dollars. Sometimes I buy =
books and they turn out to be uninteresting or fail to hold my attention. I=
 place it in a pile. Every couple of months, once the stack reaches around =
6-10 books, I=E2=80=99ll then donate them to a local used book seller. He a=
llows me to trade them for 1 or 2 used books from the store.</p><p>If I cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t afford books, I=E2=80=99d spend much more time at the library=
. I=E2=80=99d download them from libgen. I=E2=80=99d physically steal them =
if I had to. </p><p>I don=E2=80=99t finish every book I start. I skim. I=E2=
=80=99ll read a chunk of a book, place it on my shelf, and then pick it up =
two years later and continue. There have been a couple of occasions where I=
=E2=80=99d read the first page of a book, found it dull, and donated it. Mo=
re than a year later, I bought it again, and read the whole thing in a few =
days. Sometimes, you have to be ready for a book.</p><p>Most of what you re=
ad won=E2=80=99t be especially interesting or insightful. You have to crush=
 a lot of rock to get to the gems. Deep learning demands effort. If you wan=
t to possess a large mental universe of knowledge from which to draw, you h=
ave to consume a lot of information. This requires focused reading.</p><p><=
span>I=E2=80=99ll close with this excellent line from James Clear, who </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-tim-ferriss-show/id=
863897795?i=3D1000592431628" rel=3D"">said</a><span> to Tim Ferriss (on a p=
odcast I greatly enjoyed): </span></p><blockquote><p><em>=E2=80=9CAlmost ev=
ery idea that you have is downstream from what you consume. When you choose=
 who to follow on Twitter, what book to read, what podcast to listen to, yo=
u=E2=80=99re choosing your future thoughts.=E2=80=9D</em></p></blockquote><=
